.Dd May 31, 2026
.Dt UMERGE 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm umerge
.Nd interactive two-way and three-way directory comparison
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl m Ar tool
.Op Fl A | Fl U
.Ar left right
.Nm
.Op Fl m Ar tool
.Op Fl A | Fl U
.Ar left parent right
.Nm
.Fl h
.Nm
.Fl V
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a terminal user interface for comparing two or three directory trees
side by side.
It recursively enumerates the given directories,
matches entries by name in a case-sensitive sorted merge,
and runs
.Xr diff 1
or
.Xr diff3 1
on each matched file pair in the background.
Comparison results are displayed as they arrive;
the interface remains fully navigable while comparison is in progress.
.Pp
In two-way mode
.Nm
accepts two directories,
.Ar left
and
.Ar right ,
and displays them in side-by-side columns separated by a vertical bar.
.Pp
In three-way mode
.Nm
accepts three directories:
.Ar left ,
the first child tree;
.Ar parent ,
the common ancestor displayed in the center column;
and
.Ar right ,
the second child tree.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl m Ar tool , Fl -merge Ns = Ns Ar tool
Select the external diff and merge tool.
.Ar tool
must be one of:
.Bl -tag -width "emacs  " -compact
.It vim
Use
.Xr vim 1
to view single files and
.Xr vimdiff 1
to diff two or three files.
This is the default.
.It emacs
Use
.Xr emacs 1
to view single files,
.Sy ediff-files
to diff two files,
and
.Sy ediff3
to diff three files.
.El
.It Fl A , Fl -ascii
Use ASCII tree symbols
.Pq Sy > No / Sy v
instead of the Unicode default
.Pq Sy ▶ No / Sy ▼ .
Useful on terminals that render the Unicode symbols at the wrong column
width, shifting the display (their East Asian Width is "Ambiguous," so
this varies by terminal).
.It Fl U , Fl -unicode
Use Unicode tree symbols
.Pq Sy ▶ No / Sy ▼ .
This is the default;
.Fl -unicode
is provided for explicitness or to override a future config-file setting.
Mutually exclusive with
.Fl -ascii .
.It Fl V , Fl -version
Print version and copyright information to standard output and exit 0.
.It Fl h , Fl -help
Print a usage summary to standard output and exit 0.
.El
.Sh DISPLAY
The terminal is divided into two or three equal-width columns separated
by vertical bars.
The header row shows the absolute path of each root directory.
A status bar at the bottom of the screen shows the current cursor
position, whether background comparison is still running, and a summary
of available key bindings.
.Ss Tree symbols
Each directory entry is preceded by a two-character symbol, by default the
Unicode
.Sy ▶
/
.Sy ▼
triangles
.Pq Fl -ascii No falls back to Sy > No / Sy v :
.Bl -tag -width "▶ (unicode) / > (ascii)  "
.It ▶ No (unicode) / Sy > No (ascii)
The directory is collapsed and its children are not shown.
.It ▼ No (unicode) / Sy v No (ascii)
The directory is expanded and its children are visible below it.
.It (two spaces)
The entry is a regular file.
.El
Entries are indented two spaces per level of depth.
.Ss Colors
.Bl -tag -width "Blue  "
.It White
The entry is present on all sides.
File contents are identical, or comparison has not yet completed.
.It Blue
The entry is present on all sides and file contents differ.
In three-way mode only the columns adjacent to a differing pair are
highlighted: if
.Ar left
differs from
.Ar parent ,
the left and center columns are blue; if
.Ar right
differs from
.Ar parent ,
the center and right columns are blue.
Both pairs may be blue simultaneously.
.It Green
The entry is absent from at least one side.
Columns where it is present are highlighted green; absent columns are
blank.
.El
.Ss Diff counts
Once a file comparison completes, a count is appended after the filename:
.Bl -tag -width "= "
.It =
Zero differences; files are identical.
.It Ar n
Files differ in
.Ar n
hunks.
.El
In two-way mode the count appears in the left column.
In three-way mode the left column shows the count of hunks between
.Ar left
and
.Ar parent ,
and the right column shows the count between
.Ar right
and
.Ar parent .
.Sh KEY BINDINGS
.Bl -tag -width "Page Down  "
.It Ic Up , k
Move the cursor up one row.
Scrolls the view if the cursor is at the top of the viewport.
.It Ic Down , j
Move the cursor down one row.
Scrolls the view if the cursor is at the bottom of the viewport.
.It Ic Page Up
Scroll the view up one page.
The cursor is clamped to remain within the new viewport.
.It Ic Page Down
Scroll the view down one page.
The cursor is clamped to remain within the new viewport.
.It Ic Left , Right
Collapse or expand the directory at the cursor.
Has no effect on file entries.
.It Ic Enter
If the cursor is on a directory, collapse or expand it.
.Pp
If the cursor is on a file,
.Nm
suspends its display, opens the matched file or files in the configured
diff/merge tool (see
.Fl m ) ,
and resumes when the tool exits.
The command invoked depends on how many sides have the file:
.Bl -tag -width "Three files  " -offset indent -compact
.It One file
.Xr vim 1
.Ar file
(or
.Xr emacs 1
.Ar file )
.It Two files
.Xr vimdiff 1
.Ar left right
(or
.Sy ediff-files )
.It Three files
.Xr vimdiff 1
.Ar left parent right
(or
.Sy ediff3 )
.El
.It Ic a
In two-way mode, copy the entry at the cursor from
.Ar left
to
.Ar right .
.Pp
In three-way mode, prompts
.Dq Copy from A (left) to:
press
.Ic b
to copy to
.Ar right
or
.Ic c
to copy to
.Ar parent .
Any other key cancels.
.It Ic b
In two-way mode, copy the entry at the cursor from
.Ar right
to
.Ar left .
.Pp
In three-way mode, prompts
.Dq Copy from B (right) to:
press
.Ic a
to copy to
.Ar left
or
.Ic c
to copy to
.Ar parent .
Any other key cancels.
.It Ic c
Three-way mode only.
Prompts
.Dq Copy from C (parent) to:
press
.Ic a
to copy to
.Ar left
or
.Ic b
to copy to
.Ar right .
Any other key cancels.
.Pp
For
.Ic a , b ,
and
.Ic c :
copying onto a destination that already exists replaces it outright
(an existing destination directory is removed first, rather than merged
into); there is no confirmation prompt.
.It Ic d
Delete the entry at the cursor from every side on which it exists.
There is no confirmation prompt.
.It Ic q , Ctrl-C
Quit
.Nm .
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr diff 1 ,
.Xr diff3 1 ,
.Xr emacs 1 ,
.Xr vim 1 ,
.Xr vimdiff 1
.Sh AUTHORS
